The better world is already here
KOPENHAGEN – For centuries, optimists and pessimists have debated the state of the world.
Pessimists see a world in which more people mean less food, in which increasing resource demand leads to exploitation and war, and in which the growing production capacity of the past decades causes more pollution and global warming.
One of the holy texts of the current generation of pessimists, The Limits to Growth, has influenced the environmental movement up to today.
Optimists, on the other hand, claim that everything is getting better – human health, standard of living, environmental quality, and so on.
Von ihren Gegnern werden sie als „Ökonomen des Überflusses“ gesehen, die dem Markt vertrauen, der angeblich alle Probleme löst.
Aber statt Tatsachen und Geschichten herauszupicken, die in eine große Erzählung von Niedergang oder Fortschritt passen, sollten wir versuchen, alle Bereiche der menschlichen Existenz zu vergleichen, um zu sehen, ob die Welt wirklich besser oder schlechter wird.
Genau dies habe ich gemeinsam mit 21 weltweit führenden Ökonomen dadurch zu erreichen versucht, dass wir eine Wertungsliste der letzten 150 Jahre entwickelten.
In zehn Bereichen – darunter Gesundheit, Ausbildung, Krieg, Geschlechterverhältnis, Luftverschmutzung, Klimaveränderung und Biodiversität – haben die Ökonomen alle dieselbe Frage beantwortet: Wie hoch waren die relativen Kosten dieses Problems in jedem Jahr von 1900 bis 2013, einschließlich Prognosen bis 2050.
Anhand klassischer ökonomischer Bewertungen aller Faktoren von Todesopfern, Gesundheitsschäden und Analphabetentum über die Zerstörung von Feuchtgebieten bis hin zu höherem Hurrikan-Risiko durch globale Erwärmung zeigen die Ökonomen die Kosten jedes einzelnen Problems auf.
To assess the scale of the problem, it is compared to the total resources available for its solution.
This makes the size of the problem clear as a share of GDP.
And the trends since 1900 are partly surprising.
Let us consider the inequality between genders.
Essentially, we excluded almost half of the world population from production back then.
In 1900 were only 15% of the global workforce female.
What are the losses resulting from this low share?
Even when we account for the higher costs of educating women and the fact that someone must perform unpaid housework, the losses amounted to at least 17% of the world's GDP in 1900.
Today, with a higher female labor participation rate and smaller income gaps, the loss is 7% – and is likely to fall to 4% by 2050.
It is likely to be very surprising that climate change from 1900 to 2025 is expected to bring largely a growing net benefit – rising up to 1.5% of GDP per year.
This is due to the different effects of global warming. If it occurs only moderately, the benefits outweigh the costs.
On the one hand, the higher CO2 emissions were a blessing for agriculture, as the gas acts as a fertilizer. This is the largest positive effect, amounting to 0.8% of GDP.
Similarly, moderate warming prevents more cold-related deaths than it causes additional heat-related deaths.
It also reduces heating demand more than it creates new cooling demand, corresponding to a benefit of about 0.4% of GDP.
On the other hand, warming leads to water shortages, costing about 0.2% of GDP, and has a negative impact on ecosystems like wetlands, corresponding to a loss of about 0.1%.
However, as temperatures continue to rise, the costs increase and the benefits decrease, which dramatically reduces the net benefit.
After 2070, global warming will cause net costs to the world, justifying cost-effective climate protection today and in the coming decades.
However, the value list also shows that the world's largest environmental problem is indoor air pollution, which puts things into the right perspective.
Today, more than three million people die each year from indoor air pollution caused by harmful emissions from cooking and heating. This corresponds to a loss of 3% of global GDP.
But in 1900, these costs corresponded to 19% of GDP, and it is expected that they will fall to 1% by 2050.
The health indicators have improved the most around the world.
Human life expectancy hardly changed until the late 18th century.
The size of the gain since 1900 can hardly be overemphasized: At that time, global life expectancy was 32 years, and today it is 69 years (and likely to be 76 years by 2050).
The largest influencing factor was the decline in child mortality.
As an example, in 1970 only 5% of infants were vaccinated against measles, tetanus, whooping cough, diphtheria, and polio.
In the year 2000, it was 85%, which led to the saving of three million lives every year – more than would have been saved by world peace throughout the entire 20th century.
This success has many parents.
The Gates Foundation and the GAVI Alliance have spent more than $2.5 billion on vaccines and have promised another $10 billion.
Through efforts by the Rotary Club, the World Health Organization, and many others, cases of polio have been reduced by 99% since 1979.
In economic terms, the cost of poor health at the beginning of the twentieth century was astonishingly 32% of global GDP.
Today they have fallen to about 11% and are expected to halve again by 2050.
Even though optimists are not right on all points (the loss of biodiversity in the twentieth century probably costs about 1% of GDP annually, and in some places significantly more), the overall picture is clear.
Most of the topics examined show improvements of 5-20% of GDP.
And the overall trend is even clearer.
Relative to the resources available for their resolution, global problems have dramatically declined.
Naturally, this does not mean that there are no problems anymore.
Even though they have become smaller in areas such as health, education, malnutrition, air pollution, gender inequality, and trade, they are still large.
But realists should slowly get used to the idea that the world has improved significantly.
Furthermore, the value list shows us where the challenges for a better 2050 lie.
We should not orient our view of the future toward the worst stories or the loudest interest groups, but rather toward objective assessments of where we can achieve the greatest improvements.
